3. Adolescentes] Properly adolescentia extended from 15 to 30 years of age. But the term was frequently applied to persons of more advanced age. Thus Cicero, Philipp. ii. 46, calls himself an adolescens in the time of his consulship, when he was 44 years of age. Sallust, speaking of Caesar in his thirty—seventh year, calls him adolescentulus, Catil. 49. In this place homines adolescentes may be rendered “rising men;⁷' that is, men who were beginning to become important politica] characters.
